  <h2>Why we built Meter</h2>
  <p>
    Most speed tests hand you a download figure and leave you to guess whether it’s good. But a fast
    download number can hide a connection that stutters on video calls, lags in games, or buffers
    during a movie night. We built <strong>Meter</strong> because the number that appears on your bill
    is rarely the number you actually experience — and the gap matters.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our goal is simple: measure your connection the way real apps stress it, then translate the raw
    results into plain language. Instead of stopping at “<strong>250 Mbps</strong>,” Meter tells you
    whether your line can comfortably handle several 4K streams, a competitive gaming session, or a
    full house of video calls at once.
  </p>

  <h2>What Meter measures</h2>
  <p>
    A complete internet speed test is about far more than download speed. Every time you press GO,
    Meter records:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Download speed</strong> — how quickly data reaches your device, in Mbps.</li>
    <li><strong>Upload speed</strong> — how fast you can send data, which matters for calls, backups and sharing files.</li>
    <li><strong>Ping</strong> — the round-trip delay to the server while your line is idle.</li>
    <li><strong>Jitter</strong> — how much that delay varies, a strong predictor of choppy calls.</li>
    <li><strong>Packet loss</strong> — an estimate of how many probes fail to make the round trip.</li>
    <li><strong>Latency under load</strong> — how much your ping rises while the connection is busy, the effect known as bufferbloat.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    That last measurement is where Meter differs most from a typical test. We keep measuring latency
    <em>while</em> saturating your line, because that is exactly when a connection feels slow even if
    the headline speed looks great.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>
    Meter runs entirely in your browser. When you start a test, it streams data to and from
    Cloudflare’s global edge network — the same infrastructure that serves a large share of the web —
    using several parallel connections to fully saturate your line. It then aggregates the stable
    portion of each run so momentary spikes don’t distort your result. Because everything happens
    over standard web connections, the same test works on Windows, macOS, Android, iOS and
    Chromebooks with nothing to install.
  </p>

  <h2>Private by default</h2>
  <p>
    We think a speed test should respect your privacy. Meter has no accounts, no sign-up wall and no
    public leaderboard. Your test history is stored locally in your own browser, so it stays on your
    device unless you choose to export or share it. You can read the full details in our
    <a href="/privacy">Privacy Policy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Fast, light and free</h2>
  <p>
    Meter is a static, near-zero-framework page engineered to load instantly and start testing the
    moment you tap GO. It’s free to use, with no ads getting in the way of your result. We’d rather
    earn a bookmark than an impression.
  </p>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>
  <p>
    Have a question, a bug report or an idea to make Meter better? We’d genuinely like to hear it.
    Head to our <a href="/contact">Contact page</a> to reach the team, and take a look at the
    <a href="/#faq">FAQ</a> if you’re troubleshooting a specific result.
  </p>
